,"Dorset, England":"Dorset, England"},"nl":{"Abt. 1500–Abt. 1570":"circa 1500–circa 1570","1550–1587":"1550–1587","1500–1562":"1500–1562","1520–1546":"1520–1546","1525–1583":"1525–1583","1578–Female":"1578–Overleden","–1578":"–1578","1500–1570":"1500–1570","1525":"1525","1546":"1546","1578":"1578","1500":"1500","1587":"1587","1520":"1520","Abt. 1500":"circa 1500","1562":"1562","1583":"1583","1550":"1550","1570":"1570","Abt. 1570":"circa 1570","Fontmell Magna, Dorset, England, United Kingdom":"Fontmell Magna, Dorset, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Dorset, England":"Dorset, England"},"en":{"Abt. 1500–Abt. 1570":"about 1500–about 1570","1550–1587":"1550–1587","1500–1562":"1500–1562","1520–1546":"1520–1546","1525–1583":"1525–1583","1578–Female":"1578–Deceased","–1578":"–1578","1500–1570":"1500–1570","1525":"1525","1546":"1546","1578":"1578","1500":"1500","1587":"1587","1520":"1520","Abt. 1500":"about 1500","1562":"1562","1583":"1583","1550":"1550","1570":"1570","Abt. 1570":"about 1570","Fontmell Magna, Dorset, England, United Kingdom":"Fontmell Magna, Dorset, England, United Kingdom","England":"England, United Kingdom","Dorset, England":"Dorset, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Froude","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Froud  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Froud","meanings":["1  English: nickname either from an unrecorded Middle English * <i>frode</i> ‘wise, prudent’ (Old English  <i>frōd</i>) or, possibly, from Middle English  <i>froude</i>,  <i>frode</i>,  <i>frude</i> ‘frog, toad’ (compare Old Scandinavian  <i>frauð</i>), though this is not a characteristically southern word. Some of the following post-medieval bearers may alternatively belong with (2), especially the Hants example.","2  English: nickname, sometimes a reduced form of Middle English  <i>froward</i>, ‘contrary, wilful, unruly’.  See  Frewer  . This name may, however, have been confused with (1).","3  English: relationship name possibly from the Middle English personal name  <i>Frode</i> (from Old Scandinavian  <i>Fróði</i>,  <i>Frothi</i>; the corresponding Old English  <i>Frōda</i> is found only once, and Continental Germanic  <i>Frodo</i> is rare). In Normandy  <i>Frodo</i> may be Old Scandinavian (   Feilitzen  , p. 256);  <i>Frodo</i>, 1086 in   Domesday Book   was a brother of the abbot of  <i>Bury Saint Edmunds</i> and was  <i>genere Gallus</i>. Although there is no clear evidence, the possibility that the personal name gave rise to a surname cannot be excluded."]}]},{"name":"ALICE","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"ALICE Froude was born about 1500, in England, United Kingdom. She married John Foyle on 20 June 1570, in Cann, Dorset, England. They were the parents of at least 3 daughters. She died about 1570, in her hometown, at the age of 72."},"et":{"Abt. 1500–Abt. 1570":"umbes 1500–umbes 1570","1550–1587":"1550–1587","1500–1562":"1500–1562","1520–1546":"1520–1546","1525–1583":"1525–1583","1578–Female":"1578–Surnud","–1578":"–1578","1500–1570":"1500–1570","1525":"1525","1546":"1546","1578":"1578","1500":"